1 Filtering Steps

26.1% of the data is filtered out. Hereâs the steps.

  • After creating the transcription dictionary, preprocess them by removing the punctuations
  • Filter out the utterances that does not end with -ing
  • Filter out the utterances that does not start with the
  • Find out what N2 are and filter out the utterances that have weird N2s
  • There should be 7 words in every utterance, delete the ones that do not have exact 7 words
  • Filter out the ones that contain the distractor verbs
Show the code 
# process transcripts
def process_transc_dict(transc_dict):
    import string

    # Function to remove punctuation from a string
    def remove_punctuation(text):
        translator = str.maketrans("", "", string.punctuation)
        return text.translate(translator)

    # Remove punctuation from the value parts of transc_dict
    transc_dict_nopunct = {
        key: remove_punctuation(value).lower() for key, value in transc_dict.items()
    }

    return transc_dict_nopunct


transc_dict_nopunct = process_transc_dict(transc_dict)

# -ing ending
not_ing_end = {k: v for k, v in transc_dict_nopunct.items() if not v.endswith("ing")}
ing_end = {k: v for k, v in transc_dict_nopunct.items() if v.endswith("ing")}

# the start
not_the_start = {k: v for k, v in ing_end.items() if not v.split()[0] == "the"}
the_start = {k: v for k, v in ing_end.items() if v.split()[0] == "the"}

# weird N2s
weird_n2s = ["ball", "pink", "guitar", "pan"]

weird_n2 = {k: v for k, v in the_start.items() if v.split()[1] in weird_n2s}
no_weird_n2 = {k: v for k, v in the_start.items() if not v.split()[1] in weird_n2s}

# 7 words
correct_n = {k: v for k, v in no_weird_n2.items() if len(v.split()) == 7}
no_correct_n = {k: v for k, v in no_weird_n2.items() if len(v.split()) != 7}

# Distraction
not_distracted = {}
distracted = {}
for k, v in correct_n.items():
    to_check = k[:-9] + "_" + v.split()[6]
    for i in df_items["check"]:
        if to_check.startswith(i):
            distracted[k] = v
        else:
            not_distracted[k] = v

get_trial_no <- function(data) {
  data |>
    filter(PennElementType == "MediaRecorder") |>
    filter(str_detect(Label, "^trial")) |>
    mutate(subject_id = str_sub(PennElementName, -4, -1)) |>
    select(filenames = PennElementName, Label, EventTime, subject_id) |>
    group_by(subject_id) |>
    mutate(trial_no = seq(subject_id)) |>
    ungroup()
}

get_name <- function(df, name) {
  df$type <- name
  df
}

invisible(list2env(lapply(mget(file_names), get_trial_no), .GlobalEnv))

invisible(list2env(Map(get_name, mget(file_names), file_names), envir = .GlobalEnv))

unique_subjects <- list()
for (name in file_names) {
  unique_subjects[[name]] <- unique(mget(file_names)[[name]]$subject_id)
}
all_subjects <- unlist(unique_subjects)
duplicates <- all_subjects[duplicated(all_subjects)]

stopifnot(length(duplicates) == 0)

invisible(list2env(lapply(mget(file_names), \(df) {

# get important numbers, such as prev/next offset/onset,
grouped_laglead <- function(lag = 1, data, group, new_col, llag_col, default = NA) {
  if (lag) {
    data %>% group_by({{ group }}) %>%
      dplyr::mutate({{ new_col }} := lag({{ llag_col }}, n = 1, default = default))
  } else {
    data %>% group_by({{ group }}) %>%
      dplyr::mutate({{ new_col }} := lead({{ llag_col }}, n = 1, default = default))
  }
}

df %<>% grouped_laglead(lag = 0, ., filenames, next_word, response, default = NA)
df %<>% grouped_laglead(lag = 0, ., filenames, next_word_onset, start, default = NA)

avg_fun <- function(data, measurevar = "duration", withinvars = c("verb_type", "sem_type"), idvar = "subject_id") {
  avgs <- Rmisc::summarySEwithin(data, measurevar = measurevar, withinvars = withinvars, idvar = idvar)
  # round a column if it is numeric
  avgs <- avgs |> mutate_if(is.numeric, round, 3)
  avgs$lower <- avgs[[measurevar]] - avgs$ci
  avgs$upper <- avgs[[measurevar]] + avgs$ci
  avgs
}

plot_fun <- function(df, pd = 0.1) {
  df |>
    ggplot(aes(verb_type, duration, linetype = sem_type, group = sem_type)) +
    geom_point(position = position_dodge(pd), size = 3) +
    geom_line(position = position_dodge(pd), linewidth = 1) +
    geom_errorbar(
      aes(ymin = duration-se, ymax = duration+se),
      width = 0.2, linewidth = 1, position = position_dodge(pd)
    ) +
    xlab("") +
    ylab("Onset Latency (ms)") +
    # scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
    scale_x_discrete(
      name = "Verb Type",
      labels = c("Unacc" = "Unaccusative", "Unerg" = "Unergative")
    ) +
    scale_linetype_discrete(
      name = "Relatedness",
      labels = c("related" = "Related", "unrelated" = "Unrelated")
    ) +
    theme_classic() +
    # theme(text = element_text(size = 16, family = "Helvetica Neue")) +
    theme(
      strip.background = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.major.y = element_line(color = "darkgray", linetype = "dashed"),
      panel.grid.minor.y = element_line(color = "darkgray", linetype = "dashed")
    )
}

5 Bayesian Models

  • Specifications are given in TableÂ 3
  • Contrats are given in TableÂ 4, positives values are given to conditions that are expected to increase times.
  • Population level estimates for the onset model are reported in TableÂ 5
  • The onset model is visualized along with probability of direction in FigureÂ 3
  • It seems like the suggestion from the descriptive plots is confirmed in our bayesian model. There seems to be people took more time to plan unaccusative sentences. However, they are not effected by the superimposed distractor.
  • Moreover, the effect of verb type seems to be really slow. Median effect is reported to be 27.33 with credible interval [-9.57,70.65].
  • Population level estimates for the onset model are reported in TableÂ 6
  • The onset model is visualized along with probability of direction in FigureÂ 4
  • It seems like there is no significant effect found in the preverbal position.
  • What seems to be interesting is that there is an effect of trial number in both places. Participants gets faster and faster as the experiment goes both in their onset and preverbal times.
  • This is of course expected, but on the other hand, it tell us how much this might effect our results.
Show the code 
mprep_fun <- function(df) {
    df$verb_type %<>% as.factor()

    contrasts(df$verb_type) <- c(0.5, -0.5)
    contrasts(df$sem_type) <- c(0.5, -0.5)
    df$l_trial <- log(df$trial_no)

    df
}

memploy_fun <- function(df, prefix = "", iter = 2000, warmup = 1000, type="onset") {
    rt_priors <- c(
        set_prior("normal(6,1.5)", class = "Intercept"),
        set_prior("normal(0,1)", class = "b"),
        set_prior("cauchy(0,1)", class = "sd"),
        set_prior("cauchy(0,1)", class = "sigma"),
        set_prior("lkj(2)", class = "cor")
    )

    myformula <- bf(duration ~ 1 + verb_type * sem_type + l_trial +
        (1 + verb_type * sem_type | subject_id) +
        (1 + verb_type * sem_type | head))

    set.seed(42)
    m_onset <- brm(
        formula = myformula, data = df,
        family = lognormal(),
        prior = rt_priors,
        chains = 4, cores = 4, iter = iter, warmup = warmup,
        file = p(paste0("fits/m", prefix, "_", type))
    )
}



add_lines <- function(x_adjust, y_label, model, above = T, verbose = T) {
    if (above) {
        sign <- ">"
    } else {
        sign <- "<"
    }
    tmp_prob <- round(h_test(model, y_label, above), 2)
    if (verbose) {
        if (tmp_prob == 1) {
            tmp_label <- paste0("P(\u03b8", sign, "0) > 0.99")
        } else if (tmp_prob == 0) {
            tmp_label <- paste0("P(\u03b8", sign, "0) < 0.01")
        } else {
            tmp_label <- paste0("P(\u03b8", sign, "0) = ", tmp_prob)
        }
    } else {
        if (tmp_prob == 1) {
            tmp_label <- "[>0.99]"
        } else if (tmp_prob == 0) {
            tmp_label <- "[<0.01]"
        } else {
            tmp_label <- paste0("[", tmp_prob, "]")
        }
    }

    annotate("text",
        x = x_adjust, y = paste0("b_", y_label), hjust = -0.08,
        label = tmp_label, family = "Palatino",
        size = 3, color = "black"
    )
}

h_test <- function(model, parameter, above = T) {
  if (above) {
    as.numeric((hypothesis(model, paste0(parameter, " > 0"))$hypothesis["Post.Prob"]))
  } else {
    as.numeric((hypothesis(model, paste0(parameter, " < 0"))$hypothesis["Post.Prob"]))
  }
}

filter_fun <- function(df, operator, trial_number ) {
  # Create a dynamic filter expression based on the operator
  filter_expr <- rlang::parse_expr(paste0("trial_no ", operator, " ", trial_number))
  # Filter the dataset using the dynamic filter expression
  df <- df %>% filter(!!filter_expr)
}
Show the code 
m_fhalf_pv <- full_pv |> filter_fun( "<", 25) |>  memploy_fun(type = "pv", prefix = "firsthalf")

m_shalf_pv <- full_pv |> filter_fun( ">", 24)  |>  memploy_fun(type = "pv", prefix = "secondhalf")

6.1 First half of the experiment

  • First thing to notice is that trial number effect is neutralized.
  • Secondly, we have a suggestive positive maineffect of verb type, meaning that participants slowed down with unaccusative verbs preverbally. The median value of this effect is 53.81 The range of the effect however is surprisingly large: [-34.16,218.64].
  • We also find a positive interaction, suggesting that people slowed down even more with related attractors. The median value of this effect is 42.7 The range of the effect however is surprisingly large: [-17.08,165.35].

6.2 Second half of the experiment

  • What is striking about the second part of the experiment is that we see that now the interaction has changed signs. - First thing to notice is that trial number effect is neutralized. The median value of this effect is -59.78 The range of the effect however is surprisingly large: [-127.25,16.4].
